WEBVTT

00:04.900 --> 00:06.402
- Previously
on "New Amsterdam"...

00:06.502 --> 00:07.964
Fun, right?

00:08.064 --> 00:09.646
- Friends.
- Friends.

00:09.746 --> 00:10.967
[soft dramatic music]

00:11.067 --> 00:12.209
- The only thing
holding me back

00:12.309 --> 00:13.290
was this voice in my head.

00:13.390 --> 00:15.053
And Martin, the voice is you.

00:15.153 --> 00:16.935
I want to broaden my horizons
and find out

00:17.035 --> 00:18.337
what I connect with,
where I belong.

00:18.437 --> 00:19.538
I felt something.

00:19.638 --> 00:20.740
- So I'm sober, who cares?

00:20.840 --> 00:22.302
- You've been lying to me
this whole time.

00:22.402 --> 00:23.663
- Where are you going?
- To get high.

00:23.763 --> 00:25.065
- I don't even know
where you're staying.

00:25.165 --> 00:26.747
Can you just let me know
that you're not dead?

00:26.847 --> 00:27.949
- I think you may be bipolar.

00:28.049 --> 00:28.990
- Bipolar?

00:29.090 --> 00:30.032
[van honking]

00:30.132 --> 00:31.113
Out of my way!

00:31.213 --> 00:32.034
- You got to let me help you.

00:32.134 --> 00:33.556
- [indistinct]

00:33.656 --> 00:34.477
- What'd you do, son?

00:34.577 --> 00:35.719
Please, Floyd!
- Take it easy.

00:35.819 --> 00:37.821
- Please, Floyd!

00:39.103 --> 00:42.648
[soft music]

00:42.748 --> 00:45.771
[no audible dialogue]

00:45.871 --> 00:52.960
♪ ♪

01:57.122 --> 02:00.666
[kids playing, birds chirping]

02:00.766 --> 02:03.650
[clock ticking]

02:12.781 --> 02:15.165
- Come on, Iggy, crush this.
- [grunts]

02:15.265 --> 02:16.446
- Get it up there!
Come on!

02:16.546 --> 02:17.928
- [grunts]
- Let's go.

02:18.028 --> 02:19.810
Whoo! Let's go!

02:19.910 --> 02:21.052
- Whoo!
- There it is.

02:21.152 --> 02:22.374
- Whoo!
Yes.

02:22.474 --> 02:24.376
Oh, my God.
Am I vibrating?

02:24.476 --> 02:25.938
- It's just the endorphins.

02:26.038 --> 02:27.781
Now if you puke, it just means
you're doing it right.

02:27.881 --> 02:29.463
- [laughs] Nice.

02:29.563 --> 02:32.306
Oh, man, I've been lifting
for what, two weeks now?

02:32.406 --> 02:34.068
I feel like I've been
powerlifting my entire life.

02:34.168 --> 02:35.831
- Welcome to the grind house,
baby.

02:35.931 --> 02:37.433
OK.
- Oh, man.

02:37.533 --> 02:38.634
Yeah, I feel like
I'm cracked open.

02:38.734 --> 02:39.836
I feel alive.

02:39.936 --> 02:42.159
Like, everything is different.
I'm different.

02:42.259 --> 02:43.480
- Yeah.
- And the craziest thing is,

02:43.580 --> 02:44.842
is that no one else
even sees it.

02:44.942 --> 02:47.485
- Eh, most people just
caught up in their own stuff.

02:47.585 --> 02:48.967
They're just not looking
at it right.

02:49.067 --> 02:50.169
Don't sweat it.

02:50.269 --> 02:51.771
- Yeah, maybe you're right.
- I am.

02:51.871 --> 02:53.052
[chuckles]
Good talk,

02:53.152 --> 02:54.494
but these power cleans ain't
gonna do themselves.

02:54.594 --> 02:55.856
- All right, all right.
- Crush it, Iggy.

02:55.956 --> 02:57.959
- Here we go. Come on.

02:58.920 --> 03:04.026
- I have been sober for
three years and seven months.

03:04.126 --> 03:06.129
I, uh...

03:07.531 --> 03:10.915
I actually came close
to ruining that.

03:11.015 --> 03:13.018
Did something stupid.

03:14.299 --> 03:17.323
I moved in with my sister,

03:17.423 --> 03:19.426
who's also an addict.

03:20.747 --> 03:23.231
Yeah, I told myself
that I could help her.

03:24.953 --> 03:26.955
Be this big hero.

03:28.357 --> 03:31.781
But all I did was hurt myself.

03:31.881 --> 03:33.884
I stopped going to meetings.

03:35.246 --> 03:37.248
I stopped calling my sponsor.

03:41.133 --> 03:42.956
She became my addiction.

03:43.056 --> 03:46.200
[soft dramatic music]

03:46.300 --> 03:47.882
[sniffles]

03:47.982 --> 03:51.967
♪ ♪

03:52.067 --> 03:53.409
Thank you.

03:53.509 --> 03:56.252
Uh, I'm Lauren, I'm an addict.

03:56.352 --> 03:59.476
[applause]

04:03.842 --> 04:06.746
[midtempo music]

04:06.846 --> 04:09.709
♪ ♪

04:09.809 --> 04:14.556
- All right, got a medium
Italian coffee for you,

04:14.656 --> 04:16.658
light foam.
[clicks tongue]

04:17.179 --> 04:19.181
- [chuckles]

04:21.064 --> 04:23.066
Wow. For me?

04:25.549 --> 04:26.931
- My favourite. Yeah.

04:27.031 --> 04:29.034
You know, great minds.

04:30.155 --> 04:32.518
- Cheers.
Um...

04:35.242 --> 04:39.227
Just sorry
to bring you in early.

04:39.327 --> 04:41.329
- Mm.

04:42.771 --> 04:44.774
- Yeah, true.

04:50.221 --> 04:53.245
All right. Uh--yeah.

04:53.345 --> 04:55.287
All right.

04:55.387 --> 04:58.091
[soft music]

04:58.191 --> 05:00.173
♪ ♪

05:00.273 --> 05:01.815
- I would like
to begin this session

05:01.915 --> 05:04.138
with where we left off
last week, okay?

05:04.238 --> 05:06.421
You spoke about having
intense feelings

05:06.521 --> 05:08.984
of brain-numbing emptiness
and depression.

05:09.084 --> 05:10.987
- They're gone.

05:11.087 --> 05:12.949
- They're gone?

05:13.049 --> 05:14.992
- Yeah.
- Wow.

05:15.092 --> 05:17.675
That's a big change from what
you described last week

05:17.775 --> 05:20.559
when you said,
"I'm on the edge of a cliff

05:20.659 --> 05:23.162
peering into never-ending
nothingness."

05:23.262 --> 05:25.565
- No edge, no cliff,

05:25.665 --> 05:27.928
just breathing this rare air.

05:28.028 --> 05:32.014
What a time it is to be alive,
huh, Dr. Frome?

05:32.114 --> 05:33.976
- Yeah, I'll say.

05:34.076 --> 05:35.538
Wow.

05:35.638 --> 05:38.742
Um, I'm really glad
the CBT exercises are working.

05:38.842 --> 05:40.544
- Oh, no, sorry.

05:40.644 --> 05:43.308
I haven't been
doing your exercises.

05:43.408 --> 05:44.509
- Oh.

05:44.609 --> 05:46.192
OK, wh-what have
you been doing?

05:46.292 --> 05:48.394
What changed?

05:48.494 --> 05:51.518
- I finally talked to my mum.

05:51.618 --> 05:54.963
She acknowledged my feelings.

05:55.063 --> 05:56.645
Even owned her mistakes.

05:56.745 --> 05:59.128
- That's your late mother?

05:59.228 --> 06:01.691
- Yeah.
- Huh.

06:01.791 --> 06:04.254
How?
- Solomon helped me.

06:04.354 --> 06:05.977
- Hmm.

06:06.077 --> 06:08.380
We don't have
a Dr. Solomon on staff.

06:08.480 --> 06:09.701
- Oh, no, he--he works here.

06:09.801 --> 06:11.864
He's--he's just not an MD.

06:11.964 --> 06:13.346
- Oh, wait, uh, hang on.

06:13.446 --> 06:15.268
Are you talking
about Solomon the janitor?

06:15.368 --> 06:16.470
- Yeah.

06:16.570 --> 06:18.793
He's psychic.

06:18.893 --> 06:21.396
- Is he?

06:21.496 --> 06:24.440
[sirens blaring]

06:24.540 --> 06:27.404
[indistinct radio chatter]

06:27.504 --> 06:30.488
[dramatic music]

06:30.588 --> 06:32.610
[screams of pain]

06:32.710 --> 06:33.812
- What the hell happened?

06:33.912 --> 06:35.294
- Beauty pageant.

06:35.394 --> 06:36.615
Stage collapsed.

06:36.715 --> 06:38.057
- Okay, let's get her
to Bay 30.

06:38.157 --> 06:39.619
Uh, let's page orthopaedics.

06:39.719 --> 06:41.862
- You've come
to the best possible place.

06:41.962 --> 06:44.265
You're gonna be brand-new
in no time,

06:44.365 --> 06:45.747
and so will
your fellow contestants.

06:45.847 --> 06:47.910
- Porsha Grux, 16,
clavicle fracture.

06:48.010 --> 06:49.992
- Uh, okay, Walsh,
let's get her to Bay 23.

06:50.092 --> 06:52.275
- On it.
- The Miss Teen Liberty pageant

06:52.375 --> 06:53.797
stage may have broken,

06:53.897 --> 06:57.001
but it will not let it
break our spirits.

06:57.101 --> 06:58.042
- Nichelle Bartley, 17,

06:58.142 --> 06:59.805
head trauma
from falling scaffolding.

06:59.905 --> 07:01.487
Conscious with severe bleeding.

07:01.587 --> 07:02.768
- Uh, Casey, page for backup.

07:02.868 --> 07:04.491
- Anna, you're gonna be fine.

07:04.591 --> 07:05.892
- Come on,
let's look alive, people!

07:05.992 --> 07:07.214
Let's go! Move!

07:07.314 --> 07:08.536
- Hang in there, Candace.

07:08.636 --> 07:10.498
You're gonna be okay.

07:10.598 --> 07:12.060
- Where do you want me?
- Uh, over here.

07:12.160 --> 07:13.902
Head trauma, massive bleed.

07:14.002 --> 07:15.985
Turan, let's take care of
the girl in the sequined dress.

07:16.085 --> 07:17.868
Let's go.

07:17.968 --> 07:18.829
- What do we got?

07:18.929 --> 07:20.230
- Compound fracture,
right tibia.

07:20.330 --> 07:21.712
- Oh, yeah, reserve an OR.

07:21.812 --> 07:23.875
She's gonna need an ORIF.
And call anaesthesia.

07:23.975 --> 07:25.117
- [screaming]

07:25.217 --> 07:26.759
- Okay, yeah, we're gonna
take good care of you.

07:26.859 --> 07:28.521
- Alexa.
- [whimpering]

07:28.621 --> 07:30.443
- You're a warrior.

07:30.543 --> 07:33.207
These are world-class
physicians.

07:33.307 --> 07:34.849
Keep your chin up, okay?

07:34.949 --> 07:36.852
Good girl.

07:36.952 --> 07:37.733
Candace.

07:37.833 --> 07:39.014
- Is that your grandmother?

07:39.114 --> 07:40.696
- That's Marvela,
the pageant emcee.

07:40.796 --> 07:42.779
She's everyone's grandmother.

07:42.879 --> 07:44.922
Ah! Mm.

07:46.243 --> 07:48.106
- Do you know where you are?

07:48.206 --> 07:49.628
- The hospital?

07:49.728 --> 07:51.550
Am I gonna die?

07:51.650 --> 07:53.633
- No.
Uh, try to relax.

07:53.733 --> 07:54.994
- The bleeding isn't stopping.

07:55.094 --> 07:56.597
[tense music]

07:56.697 --> 07:57.678
- More pressure.

07:57.778 --> 07:59.560
- Breathe in. Breathe out.

07:59.660 --> 08:00.922
All is well.

08:01.022 --> 08:03.926
You're gonna be fine, Nichelle,
I promise.

08:04.026 --> 08:05.247
- Thanks, Marvela.

08:05.347 --> 08:07.570
♪ ♪

08:07.670 --> 08:09.773
- We need a type and screen
and crossmatch.

08:09.873 --> 08:11.575
- Okay.

08:11.675 --> 08:13.218
And that should heal nicely.

08:13.318 --> 08:15.741
- They're gonna get me.

08:15.841 --> 08:17.863
- Wait, wh--who is?

08:17.963 --> 08:20.587
- Them. The CIA.

08:20.687 --> 08:24.272
- Yeah, those two aren't CIA.

08:24.372 --> 08:26.074
- They've been spying on me
with their machine.

08:26.174 --> 08:28.176
Make them stop.

08:29.218 --> 08:30.760
- Okay.

08:30.860 --> 08:32.522
We're gonna get
right on that, okay?

08:32.622 --> 08:36.928
♪ ♪

08:37.028 --> 08:38.890
Okay, let's order her
a CT scan.

08:38.990 --> 08:40.051
Whatever's going on with her,

08:40.151 --> 08:42.254
it's not caused
by a collapsing stage.

08:42.354 --> 08:43.776
- Yeah.

08:43.876 --> 08:47.261
- Ladies.
Ladies, I've spoken to you

08:47.361 --> 08:50.184
on this day and on better days.

08:50.284 --> 08:51.626
And you know what I've seen?

08:51.726 --> 08:53.989
Grit that won't quit.

08:54.089 --> 08:58.635
So keep those spirits up
because the show must go--

08:58.735 --> 09:00.157
[suspenseful music]

09:00.257 --> 09:01.799
- Grab the backboard.
- I got her head.

09:01.899 --> 09:02.880
- Okay, I need help over here!

09:02.980 --> 09:04.983
- We're on it.
- O2 and Ambu bag.

09:10.750 --> 09:12.252
- You the medical director
here?

09:12.352 --> 09:13.974
- Uh, one and only.

09:14.074 --> 09:15.056
How can I--
- You really think you can

09:15.156 --> 09:16.618
get away with it?

09:16.718 --> 09:19.461
Stealing my mum's house.

09:19.561 --> 09:20.823
- Uh, h-hold on, hold on.

09:20.923 --> 09:23.346
Uh, is this--
is this billing or collections?

09:23.446 --> 09:25.509
- No, it was in her will.

09:25.609 --> 09:30.435
- You're saying that your mum
left this hospital her home?

09:30.535 --> 09:32.117
- Our home.

09:32.217 --> 09:35.682
She was manipulated to do it,
by you and your greedy cronies.

09:35.782 --> 09:38.405
Tricked into donating it
for nothing.

09:38.505 --> 09:39.647
Now I'm here to get it back.

09:39.747 --> 09:42.651
[soft music]

09:42.751 --> 09:43.852
♪ ♪

09:43.952 --> 09:45.975
[indistinct chatter,
phones ringing]

09:46.075 --> 09:47.977
- 'Cause I knew you were dying
to see it, that's why.

09:48.077 --> 09:50.701
[laughs]
Oh, I also got us a table

09:50.801 --> 09:52.703
at Le Bernardin
before the show.

09:52.803 --> 09:54.185
Anything for you, my dear.

09:54.285 --> 09:55.867
Pick you up at 6:00?

09:55.967 --> 09:56.749
Buh-bye.

09:56.849 --> 09:58.310
[playful music]

09:58.410 --> 09:59.752
What's up, my friend?

09:59.852 --> 10:01.835
- Um, listen,
I have a question.

10:01.935 --> 10:04.358
Do you remember a patient
named Joanne Danova?

10:04.458 --> 10:05.440
- Joanne, yeah.

10:05.540 --> 10:07.722
Ugh, what a sweetheart.

10:07.822 --> 10:09.565
We just lost her, actually.

10:09.665 --> 10:12.088
But silver lining,
we did get the house,

10:12.188 --> 10:13.490
so score.

10:13.590 --> 10:15.372
♪ ♪

10:19.277 --> 10:21.820
243
- What can I say,
we're good at what we do here.

10:21.920 --> 10:23.142
- Yeah, um, what--what exactly
did you say to her?

10:23.242 --> 10:25.985
- Oh, it's not like that,
Dr. Goodwin.

10:26.085 --> 10:27.908
What we do takes time
and finesse.

10:28.008 --> 10:30.311
Starts with a polite
correspondence--

10:30.411 --> 10:33.235
maybe a "Happy Birthday"
personalised from one of us,

10:33.335 --> 10:34.757
or a "Happy Holidays."

10:34.857 --> 10:37.480
And once contact has been made,

10:37.580 --> 10:38.722
we develop out
the relationship.

10:38.822 --> 10:40.123
- Develop out?

10:40.223 --> 10:41.485
Um, how?

10:41.585 --> 10:43.087
- Oh.

10:43.187 --> 10:44.889
I've got connections with every
maître d' in the city,

10:44.989 --> 10:47.092
hookups at the Broadway houses,

10:47.192 --> 10:49.495
and I get a great deal
from the florist on Second

10:49.595 --> 10:50.777
because New Amsterdam fixed

10:50.877 --> 10:52.219
the guy's trick knee
a few years ago.

10:52.319 --> 10:53.540
- You're, uh--you're--

10:53.640 --> 10:55.743
you're preying on our patients.

10:55.843 --> 10:57.866
- Hey now, that's um--

10:57.966 --> 10:59.268
that's very insulting,
Dr. Goodwin.

10:59.368 --> 11:01.190
- Yeah. You wined
and dined Joanne Danova

11:01.290 --> 11:02.872
until you convinced
this poor woman

11:02.972 --> 11:06.477
to donate her family home to us

11:06.577 --> 11:07.919
instead of her actual family.

11:08.019 --> 11:11.203
[tense music]

11:11.303 --> 11:12.965
- And where was Joanne's
actual family

11:13.065 --> 11:15.128
during her final months, huh?

11:15.228 --> 11:16.529
Who was there
to get her a wheelchair

11:16.629 --> 11:17.651
when she couldn't walk?

11:17.751 --> 11:19.293
Us.

11:19.393 --> 11:21.736
Who was there to make sure
her final birthday was special?

11:21.836 --> 11:22.978
Us.

11:23.078 --> 11:25.260
Who was at her bedside
holding her hand

11:25.360 --> 11:27.503
when she finally passed?

11:27.603 --> 11:30.828
Hint, it wasn't her family.

11:30.928 --> 11:32.670
Every hospital has
a department like this.

11:32.770 --> 11:35.233
Ours just happens
to be an industry leader.

11:35.333 --> 11:36.995
I'm currently
developing relationships

11:37.095 --> 11:39.038
with 30 other patients
as we speak.

11:39.138 --> 11:41.441
Me and my team,
we fill holes in people's lives

11:41.541 --> 11:44.285
that their own families
are neglecting.

11:44.385 --> 11:47.409
Now I ask you,
is that preying on them,

11:47.509 --> 11:50.653
or is that providing
a necessary service?

11:50.753 --> 11:53.016
[phone ringing]

11:53.116 --> 11:55.118
Now if you'll excuse me.

11:57.361 --> 11:59.944
Ms. Albans,
did you get my flowers?

12:00.044 --> 12:01.827
[laughs] Oh, yes.

12:01.927 --> 12:03.829
I'm so glad, my dear.

12:03.929 --> 12:06.793
♪ ♪

12:06.893 --> 12:08.315
- Hey.

12:08.415 --> 12:09.516
Excuse me, Solomon.

12:09.616 --> 12:10.838
- Dr. Frome.

12:10.938 --> 12:13.121
Oh, this about
the new disinfectant?

12:13.221 --> 12:14.683
Spring breeze.
Too flowery?

12:14.783 --> 12:16.686
- This isn't about
the disinfectant.

12:16.786 --> 12:18.007
- All right,
that's good to know.

12:18.107 --> 12:19.689
- Yeah, it's about a patient
that came to me

12:19.789 --> 12:20.811
with something
kind of concerning.

12:20.911 --> 12:22.493
They told me that they believe

12:22.593 --> 12:24.936
you connected them
with a deceased relative.

12:25.036 --> 12:27.059
- Oh, yeah, I did.

12:27.159 --> 12:29.221
Um, he was dealing
with a lot of pain,

12:29.321 --> 12:31.825
but I'm glad
I brought him some closure.

12:31.925 --> 12:34.548
- Yeah.
Well, Solomon, I--I appreciate

12:34.648 --> 12:36.711
what I can see is a gesture
of goodwill for you,

12:36.811 --> 12:38.473
but--but that kind
of interaction,

12:38.573 --> 12:40.195
that interferes
with patient treatments.

12:40.295 --> 12:41.357
It's not good.
- Oh, no.

12:41.457 --> 12:42.999
I'm helping.

12:43.099 --> 12:45.682
You see, I'm--I'm
bringing them some clarity.

12:45.782 --> 12:48.826
When these messages come,
I'm compelled to speak them.

12:50.548 --> 12:52.971
Honouring the soul's wishes.

12:53.071 --> 12:54.493
- Okay, look,
you've been fantastic here.

12:54.593 --> 12:56.256
Your first few weeks
have been stellar.

12:56.356 --> 12:58.178
But, uh, whatever it is
you're claiming to do or to be,

12:58.278 --> 12:59.340
you can't do that here.

12:59.440 --> 13:00.661
You can do it at home
on your own time,

13:00.761 --> 13:02.423
but not here, not with this
vulnerable population.

13:02.523 --> 13:04.987
You understand?

13:05.087 --> 13:06.469
- You have my word, Dr. Frome.

13:06.569 --> 13:07.790
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

13:07.890 --> 13:09.713
Won't happen again.
- All right, cool.

13:09.813 --> 13:11.815
Thanks, man.
See you around.

13:13.057 --> 13:15.360
- I'm not seeing
a hematoma in her brain.

13:15.460 --> 13:17.002
Let's go ahead
and move to the chest.

13:17.102 --> 13:20.186
[machine whirring]

13:23.910 --> 13:25.292
Now we just need
to make sure that nothing's

13:25.392 --> 13:26.614
obstructing the lower region.

13:26.714 --> 13:30.779
- When I worked my first
Miss Teen Liberty pageant

13:30.879 --> 13:34.063
in 1989, something struck me.

13:34.163 --> 13:36.587
Do you know what it was?
- No, ma'am.

13:36.687 --> 13:41.433
- Announcing a pageant
is just like being a doctor.

13:41.533 --> 13:42.594
- A doctor?

13:42.694 --> 13:45.318
- Don't think I can't hear
your skepticism

13:45.418 --> 13:49.323
despite being lodged
in this titanium donut.

13:49.423 --> 13:52.166
Yes or no?
Your job basically

13:52.266 --> 13:54.269
is to make people feel better.

13:55.430 --> 13:57.573
- Yes.
- Well, it's the same for me.

13:57.673 --> 14:01.939
You have CAT scans,
MRIs, scalpels.

14:02.039 --> 14:03.501
Those are your tools.

14:03.601 --> 14:05.944
And I have my tool.

14:06.044 --> 14:07.185
- Oh, yeah, what's that?

14:07.285 --> 14:10.550
- [singsong]
The golden voice, baby.

14:10.650 --> 14:12.072
[laughter]

14:12.172 --> 14:15.035
Oh, I've done game shows,
roasts.

14:15.135 --> 14:18.880
Oh, but the pageant
is my heart and soul.

14:18.980 --> 14:21.203
Sure, there's the fake tiaras.

14:21.303 --> 14:23.967
That's for the audience.
But for the girls,

14:24.067 --> 14:26.450
there are real scholarships,
good ones.

14:26.550 --> 14:28.292
At rehearsals,
I work with them.

14:28.392 --> 14:30.735
I get to see
what makes them shine.

14:30.835 --> 14:32.257
[soft dramatic music]

14:32.357 --> 14:35.421
Life's just one big runway, no?

14:35.521 --> 14:39.626
I get to help them find
the confidence to walk it.

14:39.726 --> 14:44.032
♪ ♪

14:44.132 --> 14:46.235
- That's a broken rib.

14:46.335 --> 14:47.476
It's penetrated her heart.

14:47.576 --> 14:49.038
Book an OR.

14:49.138 --> 14:50.720
Could rupture at any moment.

14:50.820 --> 14:56.768
♪ ♪

14:56.868 --> 14:58.090
- Ms. Cole.

14:58.190 --> 14:59.732
Hi, I'm Dr. Bloom.

14:59.832 --> 15:01.374
Um, may I have a word?

15:01.474 --> 15:03.476
- Yeah.

15:03.917 --> 15:05.099
What's going on
with my daughter?

15:05.199 --> 15:06.260
Was she hit by something?

15:06.360 --> 15:07.502
Does she have a concussion?

15:07.602 --> 15:10.225
- Your daughter's
CT scan came back clear,

15:10.325 --> 15:12.548
which means there's nothing
going on with her head.

15:12.648 --> 15:14.190
- So what is it?

15:14.290 --> 15:16.713
- Her toxicology tests showed
that she'd overdosed

15:16.813 --> 15:19.357
on a substance called THC.

15:19.457 --> 15:20.758
- THC?
Isn't that--

15:20.858 --> 15:23.842
- The psychoactive ingredient
in marijuana.

15:23.942 --> 15:26.606
Look, I'm really sorry that
you had to find out like this,

15:26.706 --> 15:28.128
but kids Kearston's age,

15:28.228 --> 15:30.451
they start getting curious
about drugs.

15:30.551 --> 15:32.133
- But you can't
overdose on weed.

15:32.233 --> 15:34.255
- I-I know it sounds crazy,

15:34.355 --> 15:35.617
but it happens a lot
these days.

15:35.717 --> 15:36.939
You know,
with all the different ways

15:37.039 --> 15:38.661
that marijuana is consumed,

15:38.761 --> 15:41.425
it's really difficult to know
what it's been laced with.

15:41.525 --> 15:43.788
- But I do know.

15:43.888 --> 15:45.470
- How?

15:45.570 --> 15:47.572
- I'm the one
who buys it for her.

15:52.338 --> 15:53.600
- All right,
some good news, Nichelle.

15:53.700 --> 15:56.003
We were able to get
your blood to clot,

15:56.103 --> 16:00.449
and this transfusion is gonna
make you feel better soon.

16:00.549 --> 16:02.491
You might feel
a little bit of chills,

16:02.591 --> 16:04.594
but it's nothing
to worry about.

16:05.595 --> 16:08.259
- Then I can get back
to the pageant.

16:08.359 --> 16:10.581
Ms. Marvela always says,
the show must go on.

16:10.681 --> 16:12.684
- Mm.

16:14.687 --> 16:16.689
[sighs]

16:18.331 --> 16:20.234
- How long have you been
competing?

16:20.334 --> 16:22.336
- Since I was nine.

16:24.379 --> 16:26.501
- Must have taken up
a lot of your time.

16:27.823 --> 16:30.266
- It's a lot of work,
but I love it.

16:31.628 --> 16:34.231
- Seems like a lot of pressure
for somebody your age.

16:35.913 --> 16:38.437
- I guess,
but the pageants are worth it.

16:41.240 --> 16:43.063
- Does it ever stress you out,

16:43.163 --> 16:44.705
you know,
having to look a certain way,

16:44.805 --> 16:46.907
having to have
a certain body type?

16:47.007 --> 16:48.429
[tense music]

16:48.529 --> 16:51.353
- Why are you asking me that?

16:51.453 --> 16:52.635
- So I'm gonna be
straight with you.

16:52.735 --> 16:55.198
I'm looking at the pallor
of your skin,

16:55.298 --> 16:57.681
your excessive bleeding,
and how thin you are.

16:57.781 --> 16:59.824
Your platelet count
is dangerously low.

17:01.586 --> 17:04.850
All of these are signs
of an eating disorder,

17:04.950 --> 17:06.052
most likely anorexia.

17:06.152 --> 17:08.054
- I don't have
an eating disorder.

17:08.154 --> 17:09.776
I'm not anorexic.

17:09.876 --> 17:14.002
♪ ♪

17:14.803 --> 17:17.606
- Hey, do you notice
anything different about me?

17:19.288 --> 17:20.670
- Your shoes?

17:20.770 --> 17:22.232
- Nope.

17:22.332 --> 17:23.754
- Did you get a haircut?

17:23.854 --> 17:25.596
- Uh-uh.

17:25.696 --> 17:28.079
- Is there something different?
- Never mind, never mind.

17:28.179 --> 17:29.081
I'll see you later.

17:29.181 --> 17:31.924
- [sobbing]

17:32.024 --> 17:33.046
[soft dramatic music]

17:33.146 --> 17:34.488
Gia.

17:34.588 --> 17:36.090
Hi, what's the matter?

17:36.190 --> 17:38.332
Did something happen in group?

17:38.432 --> 17:40.976
- I spoke to Bryan, Dr. Frome.

17:41.076 --> 17:42.898
He's not in pain anymore.

17:42.998 --> 17:44.901
He truly is in a better place.

17:45.001 --> 17:47.624
- Bryan, your deceased husband?

17:47.724 --> 17:48.826
- Yes.

17:48.926 --> 17:50.748
All thanks to Solomon.

17:50.848 --> 17:51.950
[playful music]

17:52.050 --> 17:53.071
- Solomon.

17:53.171 --> 17:54.713
♪ ♪

17:58.378 --> 17:58.538
441
.

17:58.618 --> 18:00.601
- You were right, Warren.

18:00.701 --> 18:01.822
An employee from this hospital
spent a great deal of time

18:01.902 --> 18:03.484
with your mother
during her final months.

18:03.584 --> 18:05.487
And, uh, in that time,

18:05.587 --> 18:07.730
she decided to legally
and of sound mind

18:07.830 --> 18:09.131
donate her home
to this hospital.

18:09.231 --> 18:11.855
- Wh--how is that
even permissible?

18:11.955 --> 18:14.138
- I know that
that's frustrating,

18:14.238 --> 18:16.521
and all I can say is that,
uh...

18:20.165 --> 18:22.348
For those months, whenever
your mother needed something

18:22.448 --> 18:25.993
or someone,
the bequest office was--

18:26.093 --> 18:28.196
was there for her.

18:28.296 --> 18:31.620
Because I guess...
nobody else was.

18:36.546 --> 18:38.128
- You know what these are,
Dr. Goodwin?

18:38.228 --> 18:40.171
[soft music]

18:40.271 --> 18:41.172
- I do.

18:41.272 --> 18:42.974
♪ ♪

18:43.074 --> 18:46.339
- For the past two years
I've been deployed.

18:46.439 --> 18:48.661
Been to places
you couldn't even fathom,

18:48.761 --> 18:52.066
places not easy to catch
a hop out of back home.

18:52.166 --> 18:53.187
- Sorry, I--
- Believe me,

18:53.287 --> 18:54.549
I wanted to be here
for my mother.

18:54.649 --> 18:56.651
It just wasn't possible.

18:58.133 --> 18:59.195
So I did the best I could.

18:59.295 --> 19:02.159
I--I handled her bills.

19:02.259 --> 19:07.405
I checked in on her
every spare chance I had be--

19:07.505 --> 19:09.328
before she passed.

19:09.428 --> 19:11.971
Hell, the only--only reason I'm
even able to be stateside now

19:12.071 --> 19:14.874
is on hardship leave
to get her affairs in order.

19:16.677 --> 19:18.900
Little did I know
that New Amsterdam

19:19.000 --> 19:20.261
took care of all that.

19:20.361 --> 19:21.543
- No, no, no.
Look, Warren--

19:21.643 --> 19:22.905
- You know what,
save it, Doctor.

19:23.005 --> 19:24.787
Somehow you guys turn
service to your country

19:24.887 --> 19:27.150
into a liability.

19:27.250 --> 19:29.153
And it's gonna cost you.

19:29.253 --> 19:30.354
I'll see you in court.

19:30.454 --> 19:33.778
♪ ♪

19:35.741 --> 19:37.643
- Please don't fire me,
Dr. Frome.

19:37.743 --> 19:39.245
- [sighs]

19:39.345 --> 19:41.528
Solomon, I asked you explicitly

19:41.628 --> 19:43.451
to not get involved
with my patients' care.

19:43.551 --> 19:45.613
- Look, I know, and I tried.

19:45.713 --> 19:47.616
But this gift I have,

19:47.716 --> 19:49.939
the ability to speak to souls,

19:50.039 --> 19:52.702
I can't control it.

19:52.802 --> 19:54.665
- I don't know what to say.
I--I trusted you.

19:54.765 --> 19:57.468
You gave me your word.
- It just happens.

19:57.568 --> 19:59.071
I swear it does.

19:59.171 --> 20:00.953
It takes over my spirit.

20:01.053 --> 20:03.636
It's always a vivid flash

20:03.736 --> 20:06.079
and some jolt
of a random feeling--

20:06.179 --> 20:10.885
joy, guilt, a taste or a smell.

20:10.985 --> 20:14.490
And I feel it all
in my core like--

20:14.590 --> 20:16.412
like a roller coaster.

20:16.512 --> 20:20.618
And it releases me,
and the messages come.

20:20.718 --> 20:22.540
[soft music]

20:22.640 --> 20:23.862
- How long has this
been happening?

20:23.962 --> 20:25.304
- Pssh.

20:25.404 --> 20:26.826
Um, since I was a kid,

20:26.926 --> 20:28.227
about ten.

20:28.327 --> 20:29.950
It's passed down
through my family,

20:30.050 --> 20:32.673
my father and his.

20:32.773 --> 20:35.316
That's why it's second nature.

20:35.416 --> 20:36.798
It's in my DNA.

20:36.898 --> 20:39.041
This gift, i-it's written...

20:39.141 --> 20:40.323
- This, um--
- In my family history.

20:40.423 --> 20:42.325
- This doesn't sound like
a gift, Solomon.

20:42.425 --> 20:44.888
This sounds like
temporal lobe epilepsy.

20:44.988 --> 20:49.494
♪ ♪

20:49.594 --> 20:52.338
- Core temp 37 Celsius.
On target.

20:52.438 --> 20:54.901
- DVT prophylaxis on board.

20:55.001 --> 20:55.862
- There she is.

20:55.962 --> 20:56.944
Forceps.

20:57.044 --> 20:58.386
[tense music]

20:58.486 --> 20:59.587
On our A game, folks.

20:59.687 --> 21:01.389
We only get one shot at this.

21:01.489 --> 21:02.991
[indistinct background speech]

21:03.091 --> 21:05.354
Just one big splinter.

21:05.454 --> 21:06.716
♪ ♪

21:06.816 --> 21:08.999
- Go ahead
and position the shoulders.

21:09.099 --> 21:10.761
- All right,
let's close her up.

21:10.861 --> 21:12.403
- All right.
- Suture.

21:12.503 --> 21:14.406
[indistinct background speech]

21:14.506 --> 21:16.508
Thank you.

21:19.672 --> 21:22.216
[soft dramatic music]

21:22.316 --> 21:25.220
♪ ♪

21:25.320 --> 21:27.322
Damn it. Come on.

21:28.443 --> 21:29.585
- Switch to a Prolene suture?

21:29.685 --> 21:31.027
- Nah, it won't help.

21:31.127 --> 21:34.111
This heart's been fighting
hypertension for years.

21:34.211 --> 21:35.553
The walls are too thin.

21:35.653 --> 21:38.396
♪ ♪

21:38.496 --> 21:40.519
It's beyond saving.

21:40.619 --> 21:41.961
She's gonna need a transplant.

21:42.061 --> 21:44.043
All right, uh,
let's close her up,

21:44.143 --> 21:46.086
get her to ICU,
and contact UNOS.

21:46.186 --> 21:49.090
We only got a few hours
to get this woman a heart.

21:49.190 --> 21:55.898
♪ ♪

21:55.998 --> 21:57.020
- Do you mind if I use the COW?

21:57.120 --> 21:59.423
- Oh, sure.

21:59.523 --> 22:00.704
- I gotta order psych consult.

22:00.804 --> 22:02.627
- Yeah, you got it.
I'll just be one sec.

22:02.727 --> 22:04.729
- Mm.

22:06.011 --> 22:08.354
- It's for
Miss Teen Won't Admit

22:08.454 --> 22:10.677
That She Has
an Eating Disorder.

22:10.777 --> 22:12.119
What are you supposed
to do about that?

22:12.219 --> 22:13.561
I mean, how do--
how do you help a patient

22:13.661 --> 22:15.804
who is so completely in denial?

22:15.904 --> 22:19.328
Uh, these pageants, they put
so much pressure on girls.

22:19.428 --> 22:20.570
You know, as if the whole world

22:20.670 --> 22:21.771
wasn't already
a beauty pageant.

22:21.871 --> 22:23.053
Telling women
that they have to smile,

22:23.153 --> 22:25.376
and have to be thin,
and have to be beautiful.

22:25.476 --> 22:28.660
- Sometimes all you can do
is treat the disorder.

22:28.760 --> 22:31.744
And if you get lucky,
the patient will follow.

22:31.844 --> 22:36.670
♪ ♪

22:36.770 --> 22:39.634
[tense music]

22:39.734 --> 22:41.156
♪ ♪

22:41.256 --> 22:43.198
You gotta be kidding me.

22:43.298 --> 22:44.199
- New patient?

22:44.299 --> 22:45.601
- Uh, uh, was.

22:45.701 --> 22:49.046
She just donated her house
to New Amsterdam.

22:49.146 --> 22:50.968
- Wow.
That's very generous of her.

22:51.068 --> 22:54.172
- No, generosity had nothing
to do with it.

22:54.272 --> 22:56.695
- You're supplying
your own daughter with drugs?

22:56.795 --> 22:59.499
- [sighs]
Do you have children?

22:59.599 --> 23:01.381
- No, I am not a parent,
but I do know

23:01.481 --> 23:04.605
that supplying kids with drugs
is usually frowned upon.

23:06.367 --> 23:07.990
- Wh-when my daughter was 15,

23:08.090 --> 23:09.752
she came to me, and she said

23:09.852 --> 23:12.435
that all her friends were
all vaping weed,

23:12.535 --> 23:14.798
trying tinctures, edibles.

23:14.898 --> 23:16.721
She wanted to try it,

23:16.821 --> 23:18.403
and I said no.

23:18.503 --> 23:19.724
So she didn't.

23:19.824 --> 23:21.967
Then at 16, she asked again,

23:22.067 --> 23:24.731
and she said she wasn't
asking my permission.

23:24.831 --> 23:27.054
She was just wanting
to be honest about it.

23:27.154 --> 23:28.936
I was afraid she would
buy it off the street,

23:29.036 --> 23:31.579
and it would be laced
with God knows what.

23:31.679 --> 23:34.183
So I did the responsible thing.

23:34.283 --> 23:36.586
I bought her edibles,
tinctures,

23:36.686 --> 23:39.269
weed from a reputable
dispensary

23:39.369 --> 23:40.551
to protect her.

23:40.651 --> 23:42.073
And she's only allowed
to do it at home,

23:42.173 --> 23:45.677
and I oversee
how much she does.

23:45.777 --> 23:48.080
This is what raising kids
in 2022 is like.

23:48.180 --> 23:50.183
- [barely audible] Oh, my God.

23:52.666 --> 23:55.089
Did you know that THC,

23:55.189 --> 23:57.372
the psychoactive ingredient
in marijuana,

23:57.472 --> 23:59.495
it used to make up 5%.

23:59.595 --> 24:01.617
Now it makes up 95%,

24:01.717 --> 24:04.301
making it more potent,
more addictive,

24:04.401 --> 24:05.703
and more bioactive.

24:05.803 --> 24:08.786
Marijuana in 2022 is not
the same drug

24:08.886 --> 24:10.068
as when you were a kid.

24:10.168 --> 24:11.470
- I was trying
to do the right thing.

24:11.570 --> 24:12.792
I was trying to keep her safe.

24:12.892 --> 24:13.793
- Yeah, well, you know what,

24:13.893 --> 24:14.794
buying her drugs
didn't do that.

24:14.894 --> 24:17.157
[tense music]

24:17.257 --> 24:19.440
- Kearston's gone.
Her bed's empty.

24:19.540 --> 24:20.441
- What?

24:20.541 --> 24:22.284
[suspenseful music]

24:22.384 --> 24:23.966
[cheers and applause]
- ♪ One life so it's time ♪

24:24.066 --> 24:25.968
♪ To open up your closet ♪

24:26.068 --> 24:28.371
♪ Life's not worth a damn ♪

24:28.471 --> 24:30.614
[camera shutters clicking]
♪ Till you can shout out ♪

24:30.714 --> 24:34.859
[music echoing, fading]
♪ I am what I am ♪

24:34.959 --> 24:37.863
[tense music]

24:37.963 --> 24:45.052
♪ ♪

24:46.854 --> 24:49.358
[camera shutters clicking]

24:49.458 --> 24:51.280
[no audible dialogue]

24:51.380 --> 24:54.124
[distorted]
♪ I am what I am ♪

24:54.224 --> 24:58.650
[cars honking]
♪ What I am needs no excuses ♪

24:58.750 --> 25:00.011
♪ ♪

25:00.111 --> 25:02.114
[tires squeal]
- No--

25:04.517 --> 25:08.021
621
[suspenseful music]

25:08.121 --> 25:09.223
- She leapt into traffic?
- Yep.

25:09.323 --> 25:11.105
She was out of her mind,
thanks to Mummy Dearest.

25:11.205 --> 25:12.107
Let's connect her to the vent.

25:12.207 --> 25:18.835
♪ ♪

25:18.935 --> 25:19.836
- Okay, heart's steady.

25:19.936 --> 25:21.438
96 sat. She's stable.

25:21.538 --> 25:23.401
- Well, ortho will
take her up to the OR,

25:23.501 --> 25:26.565
where they will stabilise
her shattered pelvis.

25:26.665 --> 25:28.667
I'm calling
Child Protective Services.

25:29.749 --> 25:30.930
- Really?

25:31.030 --> 25:32.052
- Look at her.

25:32.152 --> 25:34.895
- I know,
but her mum meant well.

25:34.995 --> 25:36.497
- Well, you know what,
good intentions don't really

25:36.597 --> 25:38.620
matter when your kid has to be
put back together in the OR

25:38.720 --> 25:41.303
because you wanted them
to experiment with drugs.

25:41.403 --> 25:43.346
You know, her future,
her potential,

25:43.446 --> 25:45.829
it's all derailed because
of her drug-pushing mother

25:45.929 --> 25:46.991
who meant well.

25:47.091 --> 25:48.633
- Who are we talking
about here?

25:48.733 --> 25:51.136
This girl or you?

25:53.379 --> 25:56.422
[machines beeping]

25:57.744 --> 25:59.366
- What happened?
Nichelle was doing great

25:59.466 --> 26:00.688
after the transfusion.

26:00.788 --> 26:01.689
- Severe abdominal pains,

26:01.789 --> 26:03.171
then her blood pressure
plummeted.

26:03.271 --> 26:06.616
[tense music]

26:06.716 --> 26:10.220
♪ ♪

26:10.320 --> 26:12.543
- Found a bleeder.

26:12.643 --> 26:14.646
- What is that?

26:18.130 --> 26:20.293
- Enlarged lymph nodes.

26:22.335 --> 26:25.119
She wasn't lying.
She's not anorexic.

26:25.219 --> 26:26.881
She has lymphoma.

26:26.981 --> 26:32.228
♪ ♪

26:32.989 --> 26:35.532
- There he is.

26:35.632 --> 26:38.275
My medicine man.

26:40.478 --> 26:42.501
Whatever you're paying
these nurses,

26:42.601 --> 26:44.263
it's not enough.

26:44.363 --> 26:45.304
They are fabulous.

26:45.404 --> 26:47.547
- Yeah, yeah, they are.

26:47.647 --> 26:48.909
Glad to see you're comfortable.

26:49.009 --> 26:49.910
How are you feeling?

26:50.010 --> 26:52.914
- Like a want to.

26:53.014 --> 26:56.999
I know bad news when I see it.

26:57.099 --> 26:59.622
You can give it to me straight.

27:02.826 --> 27:07.372
- The organisation that,
um, arranges transplants

27:07.472 --> 27:10.216
refused to put you
on their list of recipients

27:10.316 --> 27:13.220
because of your age.

27:13.320 --> 27:15.463
- So where does that leave

27:15.563 --> 27:17.826
my chances
of getting a new heart?

27:17.926 --> 27:20.669
- Extremely low.

27:20.769 --> 27:22.111
I'm sorry.

27:22.211 --> 27:23.993
- [barely audible] Oh.

27:24.093 --> 27:26.557
[soft dramatic music]

27:26.657 --> 27:28.599
Are they canceling the pageant?

27:28.699 --> 27:31.643
- No, Ms. Anders, we really
need to focus on you now--

27:31.743 --> 27:33.806
- Oh, honey,
that ship has sailed.

27:33.906 --> 27:35.969
- No, no, no, no,
you deserve a heart.

27:36.069 --> 27:37.851
And you know what?

27:37.951 --> 27:41.135
I'd like to talk to someone
about making that happen.

27:41.235 --> 27:42.096
I'll see what I can do.

27:42.196 --> 27:43.979
- Thank you,

27:44.079 --> 27:45.020
but no.

27:45.120 --> 27:46.422
- Well, at least let me try.

27:46.522 --> 27:48.785
- No special favours.

27:48.885 --> 27:51.668
I've had my time.

27:51.768 --> 27:54.412
Let a young person
have the heart.

27:55.894 --> 27:59.679
I've been lifting up
young people my whole life.

27:59.779 --> 28:00.840
Why stop now?

28:00.940 --> 28:05.326
♪ ♪

28:05.426 --> 28:07.528
- Okay, so your scans
came back clean,

28:07.628 --> 28:10.592
which means we can
rule out epilepsy.

28:11.954 --> 28:13.336
- So there's nothing
wrong with me?

28:13.436 --> 28:14.818
- You're not out
of the woods just yet.

28:14.918 --> 28:16.920
You know, something
is causing these visions.

28:19.604 --> 28:22.668
- It's a gift,
not an illness, Dr. Frome.

28:22.768 --> 28:25.191
Just because you can't explain
something scientifically

28:25.291 --> 28:26.753
doesn't mean it's not real.

28:26.853 --> 28:27.914
- Well, it doesn't
really matter

28:28.014 --> 28:29.196
what I can explain, Solomon.

28:29.296 --> 28:31.399
What matters is your health.

28:31.499 --> 28:33.762
So I would like
to run some more tests

28:33.862 --> 28:35.964
and start on a low-dose
seizure medication

28:36.064 --> 28:38.768
so we can pinpoint
the actual cause, all right?

28:38.868 --> 28:40.871
Is that something
you would agree to?

28:43.994 --> 28:45.456
Hey.

28:45.556 --> 28:47.299
Solomon, I know that this
is something you've dealt with

28:47.399 --> 28:48.380
for the better part
of your life,

28:48.480 --> 28:50.383
and I know that this is--
this is a lot.

28:50.483 --> 28:52.465
It's a lot to take in,
to accept.

28:52.565 --> 28:56.230
But I--I would like
to help you,

28:56.330 --> 28:58.333
if you'll let me.

28:59.374 --> 29:00.636
Solomon--
- I have someone here with me

29:00.736 --> 29:02.198
who has a message for you.

29:02.298 --> 29:05.322
[tense music]

29:05.422 --> 29:06.723
♪ ♪

29:06.823 --> 29:08.566
Your brother.
- So until you decide

29:08.666 --> 29:12.250
that you want my help,
my hands are completely tied.

29:12.350 --> 29:14.093
- Short-Fuze says he's sorry.

29:14.193 --> 29:16.896
♪ ♪

29:16.996 --> 29:19.259
- What--what did you say?

29:19.359 --> 29:20.821
- I'm being asked to tell Grunt

29:20.921 --> 29:24.426
that he's sorry
for the way he treated you.

29:24.526 --> 29:25.627
He's showing me his wrist--

29:25.727 --> 29:27.810
uh, the left one,
does that make sense?

29:30.253 --> 29:32.256
- How are you doing this?

29:43.149 --> 29:46.454
- He says he's proud of you.

29:46.554 --> 29:47.655
And he watches over you,

29:47.755 --> 29:50.999
even though you found
your strength.

29:52.521 --> 29:54.684
Stay the course.

29:56.046 --> 29:58.969
He sees the change,
and others will too.

30:01.773 --> 30:04.797
- We are shutting down
New Amsterdam's bequest program

30:04.897 --> 30:07.000
because the way in
which this program operates

30:07.100 --> 30:09.102
borders on criminal.

30:10.584 --> 30:13.608
By targeting patients
in the dementia ward,

30:13.708 --> 30:16.331
this department has
stained the reputation

30:16.431 --> 30:18.574
of America's oldest
public hospital,

30:18.674 --> 30:22.579
not to mention violated
any number of HIPAA laws.

30:22.679 --> 30:25.022
Warren Danova's mother
was grossly manipulated.

30:25.122 --> 30:27.546
And we have the power
to make this man,

30:27.646 --> 30:29.989
a US veteran,
whole in his grief.

30:30.089 --> 30:33.393
All we have to do is give him
back his family home.

30:33.493 --> 30:35.396
- Is this true?
- We had no idea

30:35.496 --> 30:37.238
Mr. Danova's mother
had dementia,

30:37.338 --> 30:39.080
because going through
her records would have been

30:39.180 --> 30:40.402
a violation of HIPAA laws.

30:40.502 --> 30:42.925
All we have access to is
what she gave us access to.

30:43.025 --> 30:45.088
- Yeah, sure, but you knew
which doctor she was seeing,

30:45.188 --> 30:47.050
which wards she was
being assigned to.

30:47.150 --> 30:48.012
- That data was available--

30:48.112 --> 30:48.973
- What more
do you need to know?

30:49.073 --> 30:50.535
Ms. Danova was not
of sound mind

30:50.635 --> 30:52.017
when she signed over her house.

30:52.117 --> 30:53.539
And if you don't want
to give it back,

30:53.639 --> 30:55.141
then I am sure we can
find an estate lawyer

30:55.241 --> 30:57.724
who will take it back.

31:04.733 --> 31:06.635
- Joanne Danova's
last will and testament,

31:06.735 --> 31:08.758
dated January 7th, 2020.

31:08.858 --> 31:10.280
According to her chart,

31:10.380 --> 31:13.103
when was she admitted
into our dementia ward?

31:14.585 --> 31:15.927
- [sighs]

31:16.027 --> 31:18.029
July 17, 2021.

31:19.591 --> 31:21.414
- So for nearly
a year and a half

31:21.514 --> 31:22.936
after the signing of her will,

31:23.036 --> 31:27.181
where she left New Amsterdam
her property,

31:27.281 --> 31:30.345
Joanne Danova was
of sound mind and body.

31:30.445 --> 31:32.868
[soft dramatic music]

31:32.968 --> 31:35.491
- Max, the donation stands.

31:37.294 --> 31:38.676
- Thank you.

31:38.776 --> 31:45.865
♪ ♪

31:55.196 --> 31:58.461
772
[indistinct speech over PA]

32:06.571 --> 32:07.873
774
- Kearston's stable.

32:07.973 --> 32:10.656
We expect her to make
a full recovery.

32:14.020 --> 32:16.604
I wanted to let you know
that I didn't call

32:16.704 --> 32:18.126
Child Protective Services.

32:18.226 --> 32:20.649
- [laughs incredulously]
- But a social worker is going

32:20.749 --> 32:22.892
to be reaching out.
- Are you kidding me?

32:22.992 --> 32:25.375
- Look, I understand
that raising kids

32:25.475 --> 32:27.698
in today's environment
is tough.

32:27.798 --> 32:29.700
And I get that marijuana
is everywhere,

32:29.800 --> 32:31.943
and it is legal now.

32:32.043 --> 32:35.227
But here in New York,
if you're under 21,

32:35.327 --> 32:39.032
it is considered
a controlled substance.

32:39.132 --> 32:41.996
You said that you only
let your daughter use

32:42.096 --> 32:45.841
in your home with a supply
you provide, right?

32:45.941 --> 32:49.165
And that was a tincture
full of cannabis?

32:49.265 --> 32:52.889
A single drop could
make anyone psychotic,

32:52.989 --> 32:56.013
much less a young girl.

32:56.113 --> 32:57.856
Maybe next time,

32:57.956 --> 33:00.179
leave the prescribing
to the doctors.

33:00.279 --> 33:02.902
- [chuckling] Sure.

33:03.002 --> 33:04.865
Yeah, that's really
gonna stop kids

33:04.965 --> 33:06.967
from experimenting with drugs.

33:08.890 --> 33:10.892
[dryly] Thanks for your help.

33:11.933 --> 33:14.196
[tense music]

33:14.296 --> 33:17.160
- Yeah, well, my mother used
to give me drugs and alcohol

33:17.260 --> 33:19.083
when I was a teenager.

33:19.183 --> 33:22.287
♪ ♪

33:22.387 --> 33:26.011
Try to win my affection.

33:26.111 --> 33:29.115
I spent my whole life trying
to dig myself out of that hole.

33:30.998 --> 33:32.339
You want
to help her experiment,

33:32.439 --> 33:35.624
help her experiment
with not taking drugs.

33:35.724 --> 33:37.666
'Cause, yeah,
it might not work,

33:37.766 --> 33:39.749
but this right here,

33:39.849 --> 33:41.431
this is the alternative.

33:41.531 --> 33:47.659
♪ ♪

33:51.904 --> 33:53.086
- How you feeling?

33:53.186 --> 33:55.649
- What happened?

33:55.749 --> 33:57.852
- We had to take you in
for surgery,

33:57.952 --> 34:00.855
and in doing so,
I found several lymph nodes

34:00.955 --> 34:02.377
that were severely inflamed.

34:02.477 --> 34:06.062
It turns out you have
Hodgkin's lymphoma.

34:06.162 --> 34:07.304
Cancer.

34:07.404 --> 34:09.827
[soft dramatic music]

34:09.927 --> 34:12.470
We caught it very early,

34:12.570 --> 34:14.152
and treating it is gonna be
a tough road,

34:14.252 --> 34:15.874
but I know that you're tougher.

34:15.974 --> 34:21.482
♪ ♪

34:21.582 --> 34:23.584
I owe you an apology.

34:24.786 --> 34:28.731
As your doctor,
I made a mistake.

34:28.831 --> 34:32.335
I let my prejudices
inform my diagnosis.

34:32.435 --> 34:34.098
I assumed something
that I shouldn't have

34:34.198 --> 34:37.622
because you were in a pageant.

34:37.722 --> 34:41.427
I was as judgy as the people
I was ranting about.

34:41.527 --> 34:44.410
And for that, I'm sorry.

34:49.056 --> 34:50.398
- You know,
for the final three,

34:50.498 --> 34:53.122
there's an interview portion?

34:53.222 --> 34:56.165
Want to know what my answer to
the "who inspires you" question

34:56.265 --> 34:58.649
was going to be?

34:58.749 --> 34:59.850
- Yeah, absolutely, I do.

34:59.950 --> 35:02.854
- It was Dorothy Klenke Nash.

35:02.954 --> 35:04.956
- Ah.

35:05.798 --> 35:08.141
- The first female
neurosurgeon.

35:08.241 --> 35:10.944
She trained right here
in New York,

35:11.044 --> 35:13.547
and started practicing in 1928.

35:13.647 --> 35:19.755
♪ ♪

35:19.855 --> 35:21.798
- You go, girl.
[cheers and applause]

35:21.898 --> 35:24.081
[laughing]

35:24.181 --> 35:27.645
Ah, look at Orderly Brenner go.

35:27.745 --> 35:29.888
The man's a gladiator!

35:29.988 --> 35:31.610
[laughing]

35:31.710 --> 35:33.893
[cheers and laughter]

35:33.993 --> 35:35.816
And Nurse Faldo,

35:35.916 --> 35:38.259
a vision in sage.

35:38.359 --> 35:41.443
Tell us, Amelia, what is
your favourite part of the job?

35:43.205 --> 35:44.507
- My paycheck, Marvela.

35:44.607 --> 35:45.908
[laughter]

35:46.008 --> 35:47.190
- Lies, you tell.

35:47.290 --> 35:49.473
She's a giver to the core.

35:49.573 --> 35:50.875
Isn't that right, everybody?

35:50.975 --> 35:54.720
And Nurse Zambrano,
I don't have to tell you.

35:54.820 --> 35:58.725
You've already been blown away
by those hot pink Crocs

35:58.825 --> 36:00.967
with the fabulous Jibbitz
on them.

36:01.067 --> 36:02.930
[tender music]

36:03.030 --> 36:05.293
- [chuckles]

36:05.393 --> 36:12.282
♪ ♪

36:15.966 --> 36:18.830
- Oh, and Dr. Monique,

36:18.930 --> 36:21.854
looking so chic
in her new frames.

36:24.137 --> 36:26.880
- Mr. Reynolds, you've made
significant improvement,

36:26.980 --> 36:28.682
but in the opinion
of your psychiatric team,

36:28.782 --> 36:30.285
you are not yet
fully stabilised.

36:30.385 --> 36:32.287
Therefore, you are hereby
ordered to remain

36:32.387 --> 36:34.810
under psychiatric supervision
a further two weeks.

36:34.910 --> 36:36.012
- Ha-hang on.

36:36.112 --> 36:37.414
That's not right.

36:37.514 --> 36:38.935
I've done
what they've told me--

36:39.035 --> 36:40.658
- Mr. Reynolds,
you've stated your case.

36:40.758 --> 36:42.059
- No.

36:42.159 --> 36:44.743
I didn't ask to be here.

36:44.843 --> 36:46.986
They put me in here.

36:47.086 --> 36:48.187
They have treated me.

36:48.287 --> 36:50.150
Now I just want to go home.

36:50.250 --> 36:51.832
I can take care of myself,
Your Honour.

36:51.932 --> 36:53.314
- I cannot, at this juncture,

36:53.414 --> 36:55.476
release you
to your own recognisance.

36:55.576 --> 36:58.200
If you have family you can
stay with who can care for you

36:58.300 --> 37:00.723
and monitor your condition
as you continue to adjust,

37:00.823 --> 37:03.847
I will consent to release you
into their aegis,

37:03.947 --> 37:05.689
but that's the best I can do.

37:05.789 --> 37:07.732
[soft music]

37:07.832 --> 37:09.054
- I don't have any family.

37:09.154 --> 37:10.976
♪ ♪

37:11.076 --> 37:13.159
I'm all I got.

37:15.401 --> 37:17.384
- Very well.
Then you are ordered--

37:17.484 --> 37:18.746
- That's not true.

37:18.846 --> 37:20.548
I'm his son, Your Honour.

37:20.648 --> 37:22.511
I can take care of him.

37:22.611 --> 37:24.353
He can come home with me.

37:24.453 --> 37:27.477
- Mr. Reynolds, do you comply?

37:27.577 --> 37:32.043
♪ ♪

37:32.143 --> 37:33.404
- Yes, Your Honour.

37:33.504 --> 37:37.189
♪ ♪

37:40.834 --> 37:42.376
- I'm sorry, Warren.

37:42.476 --> 37:44.418
I know this wasn't
what you wanted,

37:44.518 --> 37:46.821
but I'm not
giving up the fight.

37:46.921 --> 37:48.223
Okay?
As long as I'm

37:48.323 --> 37:51.027
medical director, I'm gonna--

37:51.127 --> 37:52.068
- Mr. Danova.

37:52.168 --> 37:53.830
- You know what,
leave me alone.

37:53.930 --> 37:55.552
- Look, you don't
owe me anything,

37:55.652 --> 37:57.235
but is it possible
to talk for a minute?

37:57.335 --> 37:58.756
- Ken, I think
you've said enough.

37:58.856 --> 38:01.520
- It's all going to veterans.

38:01.620 --> 38:03.242
- Excuse me?
- All the proceeds

38:03.342 --> 38:05.044
from the sale
of your mum's home is going

38:05.144 --> 38:09.210
to New Amsterdam's
Wounded Veterans program.

38:09.310 --> 38:13.856
Your mother was adamant
about that stipulation.

38:13.956 --> 38:15.458
We spent a lot
of time together,

38:15.558 --> 38:19.302
and you were always at the
centre of every conversation.

38:19.402 --> 38:21.986
She could not have been
more proud of your service.

38:22.086 --> 38:24.950
[soft dramatic music]

38:25.050 --> 38:26.031
♪ ♪

38:26.131 --> 38:28.154
Hey.

38:28.254 --> 38:30.276
I may have been here for her,

38:30.376 --> 38:34.181
but it's you
who gave her peace in the end.

38:36.104 --> 38:38.286
I'd be happy to share
as much as I can.

38:38.386 --> 38:41.110
Whatever you want to know
about our time together.

38:44.634 --> 38:46.497
- Yeah, I think
I'll take you up on that.

38:46.597 --> 38:50.542
♪ ♪

38:50.642 --> 38:52.625
- Uh, thanks again
for the early drop-off.

38:52.725 --> 38:55.188
The daily logistics
of coparenting

38:55.288 --> 38:56.830
are nothing short
of running a circus.

38:56.930 --> 38:59.033
- Kid coordination is an ever
moving goal post, I get it.

38:59.133 --> 39:00.595
This is for Sameera's
science project.

39:00.695 --> 39:02.557
- Okay.
- So have fun with that,

39:02.657 --> 39:05.000
Bill Nye.
- Thanks.

39:05.100 --> 39:06.762
You good?
- Yeah, yeah.

39:06.862 --> 39:08.485
Well, you know, I did, uh--

39:08.585 --> 39:10.487
I did have to transfer
a psychic janitor

39:10.587 --> 39:13.691
to our holistic medicine
department today, where, uh,

39:13.791 --> 39:15.333
I think he'll actually
fit in really nicely.

39:15.433 --> 39:17.937
- Mm-hmm.
- So, you know, I'm good, yeah.

39:18.037 --> 39:19.699
Just one of those days.

39:19.799 --> 39:21.801
- Hm.

39:23.243 --> 39:25.026
- What?
- You--

39:25.126 --> 39:26.668
you seem different.

39:26.768 --> 39:28.550
- Oh, yeah?

39:28.650 --> 39:32.695
- Yeah.
Uh, in a good way.

39:35.178 --> 39:37.161
- Well, thank you, Martin.

39:37.261 --> 39:39.083
It means a lot that--
that you noticed.

39:39.183 --> 39:41.206
- Dad!
- Uh, I got to go.

39:41.306 --> 39:42.287
- Okay.
- Thank you.

39:42.387 --> 39:43.649
- Yeah.
Bye, kids.

39:43.749 --> 39:45.752
Love you.
- Thanks.

39:53.361 --> 39:56.105
[Jim and Sam's
"Harley Davison"]

39:56.205 --> 39:59.029
Hey, I want that homework
done tonight.

39:59.129 --> 40:03.915
♪ ♪

40:04.015 --> 40:06.318
- Welp, that's curtain call.

40:06.418 --> 40:08.441
Our last teen queen
has been discharged.

40:08.541 --> 40:10.804
- And that is my cue
to bow out.

40:10.904 --> 40:11.925
I am heading home.

40:12.025 --> 40:13.927
♪ ♪

40:14.027 --> 40:16.030
- Or not.

40:17.912 --> 40:20.055
- Here we go.

40:20.155 --> 40:21.417
Vanessa.
- Hey.

40:21.517 --> 40:22.438
- What are you doing here?
- Why don't you answer

40:22.518 --> 40:23.660
your phone?
I've called you, like,

40:23.760 --> 40:24.881
a million times today.
- I've not had a second--

40:24.961 --> 40:27.144
- Mum kicked it.

40:27.244 --> 40:28.185
- What?

40:28.285 --> 40:29.627
- Mum's dead.

40:29.727 --> 40:33.192
- ♪ To forget the feeling
I felt then ♪

40:33.292 --> 40:34.674
♪ ♪

40:34.774 --> 40:36.756
- [sighs]

40:36.856 --> 40:39.079
Done. Amazing.

40:39.179 --> 40:44.046
- ♪ And I'm up at night still
wondering if I'll ride again ♪

40:44.146 --> 40:45.968
- [chuckles]

40:46.068 --> 40:46.969
It was.

40:47.069 --> 40:49.072
- [laughs]

40:52.516 --> 40:54.519
- [chuckles]
- Mm.

40:58.724 --> 41:00.727
- Oh, um--

41:06.774 --> 41:08.777
- [laughs]

41:11.260 --> 41:13.262
- Like what?

41:18.869 --> 41:22.054
- Oh.
Uh...

41:22.154 --> 41:24.517
yeah, like a date.

41:29.122 --> 41:31.145
♪ ♪

41:31.245 --> 41:33.949
- ♪ Yeah, I'm up at night
still wondering ♪

41:34.049 --> 41:36.592
♪ If I'll ride again ♪

41:36.692 --> 41:40.417
♪ On a pitch-black
Harley Davidson ♪
